06170nam a22010815i 9780691201498DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912014987 a10.1515/97806912014982doi  a(DE-B1597)545490  a(OCoLC)1154112893  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBS1295.52b.H38 2021 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a222.2062231 aHavrelock, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Joshua Generation :bIsraeli Occupation and the Bible /cRachel Havrelock. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b5 b/w illus. 5 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Endless War -- t1. The Conquest of Land and Language -- t2. “So Very Much Left to Conquer” and the Persistence of the Local -- t3. The Joshua Study Group at the Home of David Ben-Gurion -- t4. The Tribes of Joshua Land -- tConclusion. End This War -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow a controversial biblical tale of conquest and genocide became a founding story of modern IsraelNo biblical text has been more central to the politics of modern Israel than the book of Joshua. Named after a military leader who became the successor to Moses, it depicts the march of the ancient Israelites into Canaan, describing how they subjugated and massacred the indigenous peoples. The Joshua Generation examines the book's centrality to the Israeli occupation today, revealing why nationalist longing and social reality are tragically out of sync in the Promised Land.Though the book of Joshua was largely ignored and reviled by diaspora Jews, the leaders of modern Israel have invoked it to promote national cohesion. Critics of occupation, meanwhile, have denounced it as a book that celebrates genocide. Rachel Havrelock looks at the composition of Joshua, showing how it reflected the fractious nature of ancient Israelite society and a desire to unify the populace under a strong monarchy. She describes how David Ben-Gurion, Israel's first prime minister, convened a study group at his home in the late 1950s, where generals, politicians, and professors reformulated the story of Israel's founding in the language of Joshua. Havrelock traces how Ben-Gurion used a brutal tale of conquest to unite an immigrant population of Jews of different ethnicities and backgrounds, casting modern Israelis and Palestinians as latter-day Israelites and Canaanites.Providing an alternative reading of Joshua, The Joshua Generation finds evidence of a decentralized society composed of tribes, clans, and woman-run households, one with relevance to today when diverse peoples share the dwindling resources of a scarred land.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh  a1948 Arab-Israeli War.  aAgnon’s Moonstruck Lovers.  aArab-Israeli conflict.  aDesert in the Promised Land.  aDeuteronomistic history.  aEast Jerusalem.  aGaza Strip.  aGolan Heights.  aHebrew Bible.  aHoly War in Judaism.  aIsraeli-Palestinian conflict.  aL. Daniel Hawk.  aOld Testament.  aPalestinian Territories.  aReuven Firestone.  aThe Violence of the Biblical God.  aTwelve Tribes.  aWest Bank.  aYael Zerubavel.  aZionism.  abiblical history.  aconservation.  agenocide.  aoccupation.  aoccupied territories.  awater insecurity.  awater wars.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe